# GitHub issue workflow

One GitHub issue = one branch = one PR. Never commit or push unless the user explicitly asks.

## When starting an issue

1. Confirm the GitHub issue number (e.g. `#42`) and `ISSUE-xxx` id from `tasks/PRODUCTION_PLAN.md`.
2. Create a branch from up-to-date `main`:

```bash
git checkout main
git pull origin main
git checkout -b issue/<number>-<short-kebab-slug>
```

Example: `issue/42-github-issue-templates`

## While working

- Implement only what the issue scope requires.
- Do **not** run `git add`, `git commit`, or `git push` unless the user explicitly requests it.
- When work is ready, **print the commands below** for the user to run.

## Commands to give the user (commit + PR)

```bash
git add <changed-files>
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
<type>: <short summary>

Closes #<number>
EOF
)"
git push -u origin issue/<number>-<short-kebab-slug>
gh pr create --title "ISSUE-<xxx> — <issue title>" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
<what changed and why>

## Related issues
Closes #<number>

## Test plan
- [ ] <how to verify>
EOF
)"
```

## PR requirements

- Title: `ISSUE-<xxx> — <issue title>` (match PRODUCTION_PLAN).
- Body must include `Closes #<number>` so merging closes the issue.
- Use `.github/pull_request_template.md` checklist (RULES.md, EventBus, etc.).
- One PR per issue — no bundling unrelated work.
